The villagers say if you listen at low tide, you can hear the harp’s music drifting from the cave—a song of the forgotten. Those who dare to approach find Kael’s eyes milky white, his lips moving with words not his own. ‘Play for me,’ they beg, and he does, his fingers dancing over the strings until the air shimmers with the faces of the drowned, their names rising like bubbles to the surface.

But the sea is jealous of its dead. On the night Kael plays his final song, the tide surges into the cave, and the harp’s strings snap one by one. The villagers say his body was never found, but sometimes, when the wind is right, you can still hear the harp’s ghostly notes—the last song of the tide-singer, carrying the names of the drowned into the endless deep."
